ðŸ”¹ 1. Element Selector
ðŸ“˜ Definition:
Targets all HTML elements of a specific type.

âœ… Example: Style all <p> tags

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    p {
      color: green;
      font-size: 18px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <p>This is a paragraph.</p>
  <p>Another paragraph styled using the element selector.</p>
</body>
</html>
ðŸ”¹ 2. Class Selector
ðŸ“˜ Definition:
Targets any HTML element with a specific class. Use . before the class name in CSS.

âœ… Example: Style elements with class highlight

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    .highlight {
      background-color: yellow;
      font-weight: bold;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <p class="highlight">This paragraph is highlighted.</p>
  <div class="highlight">This div is also highlighted.</div>
</body>
</html>
ðŸ”¹ 3. ID Selector
ðŸ“˜ Definition:
Targets a single unique element with a specific ID. Use # before the ID name.

âœ… Example: Style the element with ID main-title

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    #main-title {
      color: blue;
      font-size: 24px;
      text-align: center;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1 id="main-title">Welcome to My Page</h1>
</body>
</html>
ðŸ”¹ 4. Grouping Selector
ðŸ“˜ Definition:
Allows you to apply the same style to multiple selectors separated by commas.

âœ… Example: Style <h1>, <p>, and <div> the same way

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    h1, p, div {
      font-family: Arial;
      color: darkred;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>This is a heading</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph</p>
  <div>This is a div</div>
</body>
</html>
ðŸ”¹ 5. Universal Selector
ðŸ“˜ Definition:
Targets all elements on the page. Denoted by *.

âœ… Example: Set a default style for every element

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    * {
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      box-sizing: border-box;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h2>Heading</h2>
  <p>Paragraph with no default margin or padding.</p>
</body>
</html>
